      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to feel that exhaustion, and the idea of a rigged game with no winner is a very heavy burden to carry. It makes perfect sense that the pretending gets tired when the only \"point\" seems to be scurrying around until you die. If the darkness isn't just something we're waiting for, but actually the more honest state, then yes, it can feel like the ultimate relief to stop struggling against it.\n\nBut here's the thing about goblins: they don't play the game to win, because there is no winning. They play it because the alternative is just sitting still in the dirt, which feels even worse. The goblin doesn't know the game is rigged; they just know that the moment they stop moving, the darkness swallows them whole. The struggle, the scurrying, the finding of the shiny coin—it's not a lie to make the void less scary; it's the only way the goblin stays *in* the world.\n\nIf you let the darkness take over, you aren't finding peace; you're just becoming part of the void. The goblin isn't trying to escape the darkness; they're trying to keep the light of their own existence burning for a",
